## 📖 Chapter II — The Weight of Old Wounds

Not all who travel north carry only ambition. Some carry questions burning for years.

Qyleth had been writing a new ballad — a child born without roots who rises through music, inspires all they touch, and reunites with a long-lost parent. Those who heard it wept without knowing why. Qyleth knew. The ballad was hers.

Loma carried something heavier. Her mentor **Bram** — a sage elder wizard who'd taken her in and pulled her away from the north as a child — had quietly begun using magic for things he once did with his own hands. Reaching books. Climbing into bed. One evening Loma pressed him again: *why did you take me in?* Bram went quiet, set down a tome, and floated himself to bed without a word.

The book fell open on its own. What was written described a ritual: red-robed wizards who believed their flames could only be strengthened by burning the souls of cold-born creatures — yetis, snow beasts, anything belonging to the frost. The souls would feed and empower their preferred weapon, fire magic, and allow it to burn even when it should be snuffed out. The drow had been helping them. Loma looked up from the page and understood, for the first time, why Bram had pulled her out of the north as a child. The rituals, Bram confirmed, were not over. He was too old to travel. Loma was not.

---

## 🏙️ Chapter III — The City That Never Freezes

Neverwinter defies its climate by sheer stubbornness — a volcanically-warmed river runs through its heart refusing to freeze, no matter how brutal the winter beyond the walls. The locals call it the City of Skilled Hands, rebuilt after catastrophe after catastrophe by people who simply refused to stop.

- The **Virellians** arrived as a full troupe and were installed in the royal palace's servants' quarters. Performance in four days. **Chuck** tagged along and accepted a room key in exchange for keeping to himself.
- **Seren** arrived at midnight, guided by moonlight and a restless astrolabe. A drunk guard stumbling into the trees provided her opening. She slipped inside uncontested.
- **Mumbles** arrived via Harper carriage — hired at a firmly negotiated rate — and was delivered straight to the Clockwork Stein.
- **Loma** didn't need a gate. She needed answers. A magical shop, a tome, and a shopkeeper who said *there are no Red Wizards in Waterdeep* in exactly the tone that meant the opposite — and then, against every instinct, pointed her north. To the Clockwork Stein. Lumi was close behind.

---

## ⚙️ Chapter IV — The Clockwork Stein

A tavern of mechanical obsession dedicated to Neverwinter's top inventors, engineers and master craftsmen. Gear-driven drink delivery straight to your table. Automated server droids running off a shared power spindle in the ceiling — magic ignition, hydraulic harmony. A lunar tracker on one wall calculated moon cycles to the mile. It smells of machine oil, hops, and has an electric hum in the air.

The group converged here from different doors: the Virellians through the back performers' entrance (arranged by a woman named **Elantris**, who was somehow expecting them) with Chuck in tow, Seren appearing from the midnight streets, and Mumbles already cataloguing the droids.

Small moments before the storm: Mumbles sent a beetle-bug along the bar and decoded the entire power architecture in one pass. Seren found the lunar tracker and claimed a seat by it to study the marvel. Chuck won a modest sum of gold playing cards. Qyleth clocked Chuck immediately for what he was — street-born, morally flexible, the kind of person you keep close and watch.

Then Qyleth took the stage. The Virellians opened. A round on the house from a generous nobleman primed the crowd. The Clockwork Stein came alive.

---

## 🧛 Chapter V — The Night Breaks Open

They were already there when the party came in the back way. Three of them, lean and ragged in leather jackets — pale, still, with something wrong behind their eyes. **Chuck clocked them first.** They gathered near the shadows and watched the performance. A second group hit the front door — roughed up the bouncer droid and forced it inside to fetch Elantris. She arrived at the threshold. They did not enter. Not until she let them in. They sauntered in and congregated with the rest of their pack. After noticing the Virellians on stage they pointed at them and shrieked: 

*"Kindred!"*

The lost-boys-looking miscreants underwent a flesh-ripping transformation. They shed their skin and emerged as goliath, bipedal, muscular bat monstrosities with wings for arms. Nightmares manifested in reality. Seven of them in total.

The bar became a slaughterhouse in under a minute. **Qyleth's stage anchor was ripped apart** before anyone could react. The vampiric horrors were in the room, and they were feeding.

**The fight:**
- 🎵 **Qyleth** — *Dissonant Whispers* drove one creature off the stage, cowering into the shadows
- 🌙 **Seren** — Her astrolabe blazed with guiding light; the radiant glow sent vampires recoiling
- 🪲 **Mumbles** — Beetle swarms slicked the floor with a grease trap that turned the charge into a sprawling disaster; broke the hydraulic pipes, sending running water spraying across the room — which burned the vampires on contact; fire ants lit the wooden beams
- 🐱 **Loma** — Set **Lumi** pouncing across tables to flank the horrors; Lumi got swatted into a wall for her trouble, and Loma pressed harder
- 🃏 **Chuck** — Set fire to the floorboards at the creatures' feet, giving the room one more reason to burn; shepherded what remained of the Virellians toward the stage exit


Qyleth cast **Dancing Lights** — glowing orbs streaming toward the backstage exit — to show the surviving crowd a way out. 

The building began to burn from its edges inward.

